{-# LANGUAGE DeriveGeneric #-}
-- {{{
module Main where
---------------------Import-------------------------
import qualified Data.ByteString.Lazy as B
import Data.List
import Data.Char
import Control.Applicative
import Text.Printf                           -- printf "%0.6f" (1.0)
import Control.Monad
import Data.Aeson
import GHC.Generics
-- }}}

data Request = Reqest {
      expected_outputs:: [String]
  } deriving (Show, Generic)

instance FromJSON Request

main :: IO ()
main =
  liftM (takeWhile (not. isSpace). dropWhile isSpace) getContents >>=
  \runDir -> (B.readFile. (runDir ++) $"request.json") >>=
  return. (\(Right x) -> expected_outputs x). (eitherDecode :: B.ByteString -> Either String Request ) >>=
  \files -> forM (zip [(0::Int)..] files)  (tmpFunc runDir) >>=
  \status -> print (getScore' status) >>
  (putStrLn. unwords. map show $status)
  where
    getScore' testStatus = (fromIntegral. sum$ testStatus) / genericLength testStatus
    tmpFunc runDir (idx, expOutput) = do
      input <- readFile. (runDir++). printf "input%05d.in" $ idx
      output <- readFile. (runDir++). printf "output%05d.out" $ idx
      validate input output expOutput

validate :: String -> String -> String -> IO Int
validate input1 output1 expOutput1 =
  return $ getScore input1 output1

getScore :: String -> String -> Int
getScore input output =
  case ans of
    Just 1 -> 1
    _      -> 0
  where
    ([n]: inArr:_) = map (map (read::String->Int). words). lines $ input
    ans =
      checkLength (10*n) output   >>=
      tokenize                    >>=
      matchTokens inArr           >>=
      evaluateExpr

----------------Tokenizer-------------------------------
data Operator = Plus | Minus | Times
  deriving (Show, Eq)

operator :: Char -> Operator
operator '+' = Plus
operator '-' = Minus
operator '*' = Times

data Token =  TokNum Int
            | TokOp  Operator
  deriving (Show, Eq)

isTokOp :: Token -> Bool
isTokOp (TokOp _) = True
isTokOp  _       = False

numEqualTok :: Int -> Token -> Bool
numEqualTok val (TokNum num) = val == num
numEqualTok _ _ = False

checkLength :: Int -> String -> Maybe String
checkLength len str
  | length str > len+2 = Nothing
  | otherwise          = Just str

matchTokens :: [Int] -> [Token] -> Maybe [Token]
matchTokens = checkContent True
  where
    checkContent :: Bool -> [Int] -> [Token] -> Maybe [Token]
    checkContent _ nums toks
      | null nums && null toks = Just []
      | null nums || null toks = Nothing
    checkContent isNum (n:nums) (t:toks)
      | isNum && numEqualTok n t =
          (t:) <$> checkContent (not isNum) nums toks
      | not isNum && isTokOp t   =
          (t:) <$> checkContent (not isNum) (n:nums) toks
      | otherwise                = Nothing

p = 101

tokenize :: String -> Maybe [Token]
tokenize [] = Just []
tokenize (c:cs)
  | isSpace c = tokenize cs
  | c == '+' = ((TokOp Plus):) <$> (tokenize cs)
  | c == '-' = ((TokOp Minus):) <$> (tokenize cs)
  | c == '*' = ((TokOp Times):) <$> tokenize cs
  | isNumber c =
      let
        (num', cs') = span isNumber (c:cs)
        num = read num'
      in
        if length num' > 7 || num < 1 || num > p-1
        then Nothing
        else ((TokNum num):) <$> tokenize cs'
  | otherwise = Nothing

evaluateExpr :: [Token] -> Maybe Int
evaluateExpr (TokNum v: toks') =
  evaluate' v undefined toks'
  where
    evaluate' :: Int -> Operator -> [Token] -> Maybe Int
    evaluate' curVal _     [] = Just $ if curVal == 0 then 1 else 0
    evaluate' curVal lstOp (TokNum val:toks)
      | lstOp == Times = evaluate' ((curVal*val)`mod`p) undefined toks
      | lstOp == Plus  = evaluate' ((curVal+val)`mod`p) undefined toks
      | lstOp == Minus = evaluate' ((curVal-val)`mod`p) undefined toks
    evaluate' curVal _      (TokOp op: toks) = evaluate' curVal op toks
model.body_html:
5 year old Shinchan had just started learning Mathematics. Meanwhile, one of his studious classmate, Kazama, had already written a basic calculator which supports only 3 operations on integral numbers: multiplication , addition , and subtraction . Since he had just learnt about these operations, he didn't have knowledge of precedence of operators, and in his calculator all operators had same precedence and left associativity.

As always Shinchan started to irritate him with his silly question. He gave Kazama a list of integers and asked him to insert one of the above operators between each pair of consecutive integer such that the result obtained after feeding the resulting expression in Kazama's calculator is divisible by . At core Shinchan is a good guy, so he gave only that list of integers for which the answer always exists.

Can you help Kazama in creating the required expression? If multiple solutions exists, print any one of them.

Input Format

First line contains an integer, , representing the number of elements in the list. In next line there are space separated integers representing the list.

Constraints

  • Length of output expression should not exceed .

Note

  • You are not allowed to permute the list.
  • All operators have same precedence order and left associativity, ie.,
  • Unary plus and minus are not supported, ie., statement like , , are invalid.

Output Format

Print the resultant expression. You can insert 0 or more spaces between operators and operands.

Sample Input 0

3
22 79 21

Sample Output 0

22*79-21

Explanation 0

Solution 1: , where and it is perfectly divisible by 101.
Solution 2: , which is another multiple of 101.

Sample Input 1

5
55 3 45 33 25

Sample Output 1

55+3-45*33-25

Explanation 1

which is also divisible by 101.
